body:
**Description**: when partitioning a model, some of its initializers can be used in multiple partitions thus each partition possess a copy of that tensor and cause difficulty on gradient syncing. This change does a post split check to identify any shared initializers. If sharing exist, we will keep the first initializer and pass it down to downstream partitions through Send/Recv​ ops.

A new test is also added to guard this change.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Bert model has a word embedding initializer that is being used in the first and last partition. In order to obtain the correct training result, this change keeps the embedding in the first partition and pass it down to last partition for correct gradient calculation.

**Description**
I started to use the OnnxRuntime in a C++ context and I had some difficulty building it from scratch using the given CMakeLists.txt. Two things bothered me:
- The way PythonInterp and PythonLibs was handled made my configuration crashed at some point. It seems it's a known problem with how CMake was looking for Python. It seems it changed since CMake 3.12 where the `find_package(PythonInterp)` and `find_package(PythonLibs)` became deprecated as stated [here](https://cmake.org/cmake/help/v3.12/module/FindPythonLibs.html) and [here](https://cmake.org/cmake/help/v3.12/module/FindPythonInterp.html)
- The forced installation of the OnnxRuntime. I don't know if there is a specific reason to force the installation of the library and not making it an option and if so I would love to know why. But in my case, I try to avoid any 3rdparty installation related to my work since it's easier to later change versions without system conflicts and deployments with my coworkers. 

I had to write my own CMake with modified paths obviously. I give you below what I changed, in case you want to discuss it.

**Python handling**

Before:

```
if(onnxruntime_BUILD_SHARED_LIB OR onnxruntime_ENABLE_PYTHON)
  if(onnxruntime_ENABLE_PYTHON)
    find_package(PythonInterp 3.5 REQUIRED)
    find_package(PythonLibs 3.5 REQUIRED)
  else()
    find_package(PythonInterp 3.4 REQUIRED)

endif()
```

To be clear the `onnxruntime_ENABLE_PYTHON` option will always be False for me so I didn't handle this case further in your CMake since the idea is only to change the minimum part. The `set` call is used only for compatibility with the **onnxruntime.cmake** file.

**Avoid the installation**

It's good to know I forced my CMake builtin install function to not do anything (I know it's not the best idea but it's very efficient to not do any installation from 3rdparties). I'm not sure about the libraries to link to my interface to be able to only use the API but it worked for me and it could be great to consider have this part changed to use onnxruntime without installing. I would also like to point I did that since I had undefined references errors otherwise.

**System information**

title: Java API: Fix OrtSession.close() crashing in multi-threaded environments
Update Attention op to support attention mask for GPT-2
body:
**Description**: 

Support Attention Mask for GPT-2 with left side padding.

The original attention mask has shape (batch_size, all_sequence_length) with values 1 or 0. The Attention op has input mask_index, which allows shape (batch_size), and it assumes that input uses right side padding, and mask_index has a list of end positions for actual sequence length.

For GPT-2 with past state, we also need to support left side padding, so we extend mask_index to support two new formats:
(1) Raw attention mask with values 1 and 0. Its shape is (batch_size, past_sequence_length + sequence_length)
(2) An extended mask index:  start positions are appended to the list of end positions. The shape of mask_index is (2 * batch_size) with content like `end_0, end_1, ..., end_B, start_0, start_1, ..., start_B", where B=batch_size - 1.

To convert original attention mask to mask_index, it needs a custom op (or update EmbedLayerNormalization op). That will be done later.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

Attention mask is needed to support GPT-2 batch inference.

title: Update function body initialization for ONNX functions
body:
**Description**: Today we initialize the function body during graph load regardless whether ort contains a kernel for this function. Therefore in cases when a kernel is available in ort this initialization goes to waste. This PR moves function initialization during partitioning instead of graph load. This way function body is only initialized if a kernel is not available for the function. 

**Motivation and Context**
- One of the models I am testing with contains a lot of DynamicQuantizeLinear functions after quantization. By making this change I see around 4MB reduction in mem consumption.

title: Support builds without RTTI
body:
**Description**: Supporting disabling RTTI and other options for reducing binary size were requested by customers.

The only more relevant change was the inheritance around IControlFlowKernel to avoid casting sideways in the inheritance tree. Previously, control flow kernels would inherit from OpKernel and IControlFlowKernel. Since all IControlFlowKernel were also OpKernel (and no class inherited from IControlFlowKernel only), I made IControlFlowKernel inherit from OpKernel, so a simple downcast/upcast without RTTI can be done.

I believe all breaking changes are restricted to the CPU provider and don't affect any public APIs. Let me know if I'm wrong and we can discuss alternatives.

title: fix python ep default ordering.
body:
For python bindings there is a default Execution Provider (EP) order if the user doesn't explicitly set the EP priority.
e.g. if you build ort with python binding with CUDA enabled, the CUDA EP will by default be registered with higher priority than CPU EP.
however for migraphx EP , CPU EP had higher priority by default which was backwards. (same for the ARM EP's) 
This was due to new EP's being added at the end of the GetAllProviders() vector. CPU EP should always be last.

title: Minor optimization in CUDA reduction ops
body: **Description**: Minor optimization in CUDA reduction ops. There is logic to zero out the output buffer before actually starting off with the reduction operations, but this precedes handling a corner case where-in the input just needs to be copied over to the output and hence this corner case will incur an additional "zeroing out" cost plus the copy cost. To avoid this, move the logic to zero out the output buffer to after the special corner cases are handled.

title: Add LRScheduler implementation

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
`optim.lr_scheduler.LRScheduler`, `optim.lr_scheduler.ConstantWarmupLRScheduler`, `optim.lr_scheduler.CosineWarmupLRScheduler`, `optim.lr_scheduler.LinearWarmupLRScheduler`, `optim.lr_scheduler.PolyWarmupLRScheduler` classes

Note that for all schedulers implemented, in order to be able to accept `step=0` in the input, the warmup was computed as `x = (train_step_info.step + 1) / (self.total_steps + 1)`, meaning that `+1` was added to both numerator and denominator. This prevents `lr` to be computed as zero in the first iteration (`lr=lr*(0/warmup)`), which would cause all other subsequent lr to be also zero (`lr=0*(x/warmup)`)

**Description**: Fixing bug in special case handling for matrices for matmul operator.
The special case is applicable for following cases:
Special cases below for right_shape being 2D and left_shape > 2D by flattening left_shape to 2D
Note that padding 1s in front of the right_shape can be flattened too
A: [M1, M2, ... K], B: [K, N]
A: [M1, M2, ... K], B: [N, K]^T
A: [M1, M2, ... K], B: [1, ..., 1, K, N]
A: [M1, M2, ... K], B: [1, ..., 1, N, K]^T

A: [M, K], B:[1, ..., 1, K, N]

**Description**: The kernels to copy/pack matrix A and B had an internal limit of K=128 to avoid overflowing intermediate reduction accumulators. This change hoists the zero point offset out of the copy/pack routines and allows K to be any size (still subject to int32_t overflow). The changes have no measurable performance change, but break up what would otherwise be a much larger prepack PR.

body:
**Description**: Use the file size while reading onnx models. Ensure models are loaded using APIs in model.h for consistency.

**Motivation and Context**
This serves as a middle ground between providing a large fixed sized buffer of 4mb (done [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/4020) and [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/4150)) and the default of 8kb inside protobuf. The 4mb change causes an unnecessary increase in memory usage for even the smallest of the models due to [this](https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf/blob/master/src/google/protobuf/io/zero_copy_stream_impl_lite.cc#L291) and the default is apparently slowing down model loading on Azure machines due to it's slow reads.

title: Adjustments to MPI and NCCL library discovery on build

labels.name: build
labels.description: build issues; typically submitted using template

body:
**Description**: 
- When --mpi_home is specified, parse MPI version from $MPI_HOME/bin/mpirun.
- When --nccl_home is specified, also search for libnccl.so at $NCCL_HOME/lib.

**Motivation and Context**
When more than one MPI version is available, the build will incorrectly parse the MPI version found on PATH. Rather it should expect and use _mpirun_ at $MPI_HOME/bin/mpirun.

When using the NVIDIA CUDA 10.2 base image, the NCCL header and libraries are at
- /usr/local/cuda-10.2/targets/x86_64-linux/lib/libnccl.so.2
- /usr/local/cuda-10.2/targets/x86_64-linux/include/nccl.h

This does not match expectation of existing hint, and NCCL discovery fails.

This change is needed to change base image for examples repository to NVIDIA CUDA 10.2 from PyTorch 20.03.

title: Add the framework to support prepack
body:
**Description**: 
Set up framework to support prepacking
**Motivation and Context**
Prepacking initialized constant tensor can improve performance for some operators, for example, prepacking the constant matrix B for MatMul, weights for GRU&LSTM. However, our current mechanics to support prepack has a drawback: it introduce memory overhead. 
This PR introduces a method to remove the memory overhead. It adds a virtual function PrePack to allow OpKernel to PrePack the tensors. The function is invoked in SessionState initialization stage. If no other Ops using this initialized constant tensor, it will be released.

**Motivation and Context**
MlasGemm now takes a flag to indicate if the B matrix is signed or not and the templated forms are removed.
